      "target": {
        "kind": "pull_request",
        "title": "fix(cron): re-arm timer chain on unhandled rejection",
        "body": "## Summary\n\nFixes #73166. Inspired by the approach in #73355, rewritten against current main.\n\n### The problem\nWhen `onTimer` rejects (any unhandled error outside its try/catch), the `.catch()` handler logs the error but **does not re-arm the timer**. This permanently kills the cron scheduler until the next gateway restart. No recovery path exists.\n\nThis is especially dangerous because:\n- A single transient provider error during an isolated agent cron job can kill all future scheduled jobs\n- The failure is silent — no warning, no alert, the scheduler just stops ticking\n- Gateway restart is the only recovery, which may not happen for hours/days\n\n### The fix\nAdded `armTimer(state)` call inside both `.catch()` handlers:\n1. `armTimer()` — main timer chain\n2. `armRunningRecheckTimer()` — re-check timer during active job execution\n\n### Why not the full watchdog from #73355?\nThe original PR also included a `setInterval`-based watchdog as defense-in-depth. I chose not to adopt it because:\n- The `.catch()` re-arm is the minimal correct fix for the reported bug\n- The running guard in `onTimer` already prevents chain death during active execution — the `.catch` fills the remaining gap\n- The watchdog adds significant complexity (new lifecycle, new state field, new test surface) for marginal additional safety\n- If a watchdog is needed later, it should be a separate, well-tested PR\n\n### What differs from #73355\n- Rewritten against current main (cron module restructured since PR was opened — agent-watchdog extraction, task ledger, running-recovery guard)\n- No independent watchdog — `.catch()` re-arm only\n- Includes a test that actually exercises the rejection path via `vi.advanceTimersToNextTimerAsync`\n\n**Test plan:** `pnpm test src/cron/service/timer.catch-rearm.test.ts`",
        "branch": "fix/cron-watchdog-v2",
